  "prompt": "When people say \"Maths\" instead of \"Math\" are they indicating plurality in some way?",
  "response": "Yes, when people say \"maths\" instead of \"math,\" they are indicating plurality in a way. The term \"math\" is commonly used in American English, while \"maths\" is the term used in British English, as it stands for \"mathematics.\" The \"s\" at the end of \"maths\" reflects the word being a plural noun, emphasizing that mathematics consists of various branches and topics. So, while both terms refer to the same subject, \"maths\" can be seen as acknowledging that mathematics is a collection of multiple areas of study.",
